  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And they tarried",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It should rather be rendered in the imperative mood: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "And tarry ye until the afternoon. So they did eat both of them",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And tarry ye until the afternoon. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "So they did eat both of them",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The imperative ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "comfort thine heart",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is in the singular because only the man and the father-in-law are represented throughout as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "eating and drinking both of them together.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The imperative ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "tarry ye is in",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the plural because it applies to the wife as well as the man. Judges 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And even in the morning of the fifth day he suffered himself to be induced to remain till the afternoon. התמהמהוּ is an imperative, \"Tarry till the day turns,\" i.e., till mid-day is past. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
